data.content:
Use `Request.Body` with the multipart content-type boundary to stream sections directly to disk, bypassing `IFormFile`'s memory buffer:

**1. Increase limits in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

**2. Stream to disk using `MultipartReader`:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue;
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize real name as needed
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(savePath, FileMode.Create);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**3. Disable form binding (critical):**

Add `[DisableRequestSizeLimit]` or the attribute equivalent for minimal APIs — the `DisableAntiforgery()` above already avoids form token parsing. The key is that you **never bind `IFormFile`** — reading `MultipartReader` yourself means ASP.NET Core won't buffer the body.

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads the raw stream in chunks (default 16 KB), writing each chunk to the `FileStream` — peak memory stays flat regardless of file size.
